{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512144"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11852"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11852"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.11,0.09,0.61,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58987"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4452"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11852"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44398"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1665"},{"type":"tags","id":"1667"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42671"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58987"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13 month old baby is brought in with his parents to the General Practice clinic with persistent diarrhoea and concerns about his delayed growth, more so in the last 2 months.  The parents report that the baby is always very difficult to settle despite all their methods.  He was born via a home-birth and he was not given any immunisations due to his parents beliefs.  He was breast-fed up to 11-months of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, scaly erythematous plaques are observed over hands, feet, anogenital area, and around the lower half of the child\u0027s face but sparing the face in U-shaped pattern.  The baby lacks hair on his head and the parents stated that it dropped out over the last 2 months. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory testing shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin 20 \u00b5mol/L (3-17)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin 30 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT 225 U/L(\u0026lt;42)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP 15 U/L (30-120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT 56 U/L(\u0026lt; 45).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biotin deficiency","Necrolytic migratory erythema","Psoriasis","Acrodermatitis enteropathica","Pellagra"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of zinc deficiency after being weaned from being breast-fed. \u003Cstrong\u003EAcrodermatitis enteropathica\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited form of zinc deficiency characterized by the triad of periorificial and acral dermatitis, alopecia, and diarrhoea. It is autosomal recessive.  Additional features include growth delay, recurrent infections, and neuropsychiatric symptoms. The measurement of plasma zinc levels helps to confirm the diagnosis. A level of less than 70 microgram/L in fasting or less than 65 microgram/L in non-fasting individuals is considered\u00a0diagnostic. Low albumin levels may lead to a low zinc level; therefore, serum albumin\u00a0also\u00a0should be measured. Measurement of alkaline phosphatase, a zinc-dependent enzyme,\u00a0also\u00a0may be useful in some cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiotin deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar features including dermatitis, alopecia, and neurological symptoms. However, the characteristic periorificial distribution and low ALP are more suggestive of zinc deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrolytic migratory erythema\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic rash associated with glucagonoma - an alpha-cell tumour of the pancreatic islets and typically presents in middle age adults. The rash has a different pattern and is not typically periorificial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the systemic features, growth delay, or biochemical abnormalities. Alopecia can be associated when the scalp is involved but is not common with psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPellagra\u003C/strong\u003E (niacin deficiency) can present with dermatitis, diarrhoea, and neurological symptoms. However, the dermatitis typically affects sun-exposed areas and would not cause the low ALP seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcrodermatitis enteropathic can be congenital or acquired from inadequate zinc intake or excessive loss.  Treatment with oral zinc treatment results in resolution of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acrodermatitis enteropathica is characterized by the triad of periorificial dermatitis, alopecia, and diarrhoea.","Low alkaline phosphatase can be a marker of zinc deficiency as it is a zinc-dependent enzyme.","Zinc deficiency can present with growth delay, recurrent infections, and neuropsychiatric symptoms."],"references":["Maverakis E, Fung MA, Lynch PJ, et al. Acrodermatitis enteropathica and an overview of zinc metabolism. J Am Acad Dermatol 2007;56:116\u201324. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17190629/","Ngan V, Gangakhedkar A, Oakley A. Acrodermatitis enteropathica. DermNet NZ.  2019.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/acrodermatitis-enteropathica"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44398"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11852"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44398"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T00:10:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T00:10:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4452"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58987"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Appl